BALI_(638)
description: Le monastère Brahma Vihara Arama, est le seul monastère bouddhique à Bali situé en pleine nature  sur une colline au Sud Ouest de Lovina.  Cet ensemble architectural est très différent des temples balinais et le jardin, orné de statures impressionnantes vaut le déplacement. On y aperçoit des moines en prières . Il dispose de décorations colorées, un toit orange, des statues de Buddha, des sculptures balinaises et des gardiens aux portes. Cette belle structure se trouve dans un endroit  magnifique dotée de grands arbres de pin, des pelouses taillées, des jardins de fleurs bien entretenus et d'une vue plongeante sur la vallée, les champs de riz et la mer.

title: a great place
description: Sjaki-Tari-Us in central Ubud, a great little warung that is also cheap. It is run by a Dutch charity as a school for special needs children and staffed mainly by young Dutch volunteers. Such a great initiative in a country such as this where children like these are generally hidden away and do not have the opportunities as they would have done in western countries. As a teacher in that field myself I was of course very interested. And impressed with what I saw. www.sjakitarius.nl/

Ronyi the Reclined.
description:
Our handsome (but extremely naughty) cat Ronyi in our garden at Villa Taman Damai (Ubud, Bali).

Ronyi was taken in as a kitten after being found meowing in trash at the side of the road. He was taken in only a few weeks after our previous cat Boddah was sadly killed by a motorist.

Ronyi has been sterilised and immunised, something that does not occur often enough in Bali and we hope that our neighbours will follow our lead.

title: Religiosidad - In explore
description:
Mientras que Indonesia es el país con mayor población musulmana del mundo,en Bali ,como excepción, se practica una religión mezcla entre el hinduismo ,animismo y las tradiciones antiguas.
Una de sus prácticas diarias más importantes,consiste en depositar ofrendas (consistentes en flores y algo de comida) a sus Dioses. 
Estas ofrendas se colocan en diferentes lugares de la casa (en la cocina, las escaleras, en el suelo..), en los templos de cada casa , en la calle, delante de la puerta de su tienda, etc, todos ellos con diferentes intenciones (para tener suerte, para evitar peligro, para “conseguir” más ventas…).
Templo en Kuta - BALI

Reflections of Bali
description: A jukung or canoe also known as cadik is a small wooden Indonesian outrigger canoe. It is a traditional fishing boat The colourful traditional fishing boats that line the coastal. These graceful vessels use only one main cloth sail and in favourable winds can skim them ocean’s surface at a fairly rapid pace. The Balinese generally use jukung for fishing. These boats will venture out into the coastal waters in the evening and return with their catch before sunrise to sell at local seafood markets. However, the impact of tourism has meant that many of the island’s traditional fishermen can now supplement their limited incomes by taking paying passengers to surf and snorkel at offshore reefs and neighbouring islands. Source www.tanahlot.net/home/index.php?option=com_content&vi.... en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jukung Bali_238.3

title: Inner Temples - Taman Ayun Temple 1800
description: Built in 1634, Pura Taman Ayun was the main temple of the Mengwi kingdom. The temple was built as a place to worship the royal ancestors. Meru, the multi-tiered tower-shrines, are dedicated to gods and ancestors; the tallest tower has eleven tiers and represents Bali’s second-highest mountain, Gunung Batukau. title: Trunyan village cemetery, Lake Batur, Bali
description:
The village of Trunyan is squeezed tightly between the lake and the outer crater rim of Batur, an almighty volcano in Kintamani. This is a Bali Aga village, inhabited by descendants of the original Balinese, the people who predate the arrival of the Hindu Majapahit kingdom in the 16th century. It is famous for the Pura Pancering Jagat temple, but unfortunately visitors are not allowed inside. There are also a couple of traditional Bali Aga-style dwellings, and a large banyan tree, which is said to be more than 1,100 years old. At Kuban sub-village close to Trunyan is a mysterious cemetery that is separated by the lake and accessible only by boat - there is no path along the steep walls of the crater rim.

The village of Trunyan itself is situated at the edge of Batur Lake. This location is inaccessible except by boat, and it takes around half an hour across the calm waters. Getting to Lake Batur takes around two hours drive to the northeast of Denpasar along the main road to Buleleng and through Bangli Regency.

Unlike the Balinese people, the people of Trunyan do not cremate or bury their dead, but just lay them out in bamboo cages to decompose, although strangely there is no stench. A macabre collection of skulls and bones lies on the stone platform and the surrounding areas.

The dead bodies don't produce bad smells because of the perfumed scents from a huge Taru Menyan tree growing nearby. Taru means 'tree' and Menyan means 'nice smell'. The name of Terunyan was also derived from these two words.

The women from Trunyan are prohibited from going to the cemetery when a dead body is carried there. This follows the deeply rooted belief that if a woman comes to the cemetery while a corpse is being carried there, there will be a disaster in the village, for example a landslide or a volcanic eruption. Such events have been frequent in the village's history, but whether women had anything to do with it is a matter of opinion...

You can visit both the village of Trunyan and the Kuban cemetery by chartered boat from Kedisan. Sadly, nowadays the boat trips are now blatant tourist traps, as touts and guides strongly urge you to donate your cash to the temple project or leave a donation for the dead. These touts ruin an otherwise fascinating experience.

title: Sanur Sunrise 1788
description: Bali, that volcanic tropical paradise just eight degrees south of the equator, is in the path of the west monsoon from October to April, with heavy rains typical from December through March. Sanur Beach, on the east coast, is well situated for tropical sunrises over the jukung, the brightly painted outrigger canoes, that are anchored on the shallow waters. There are also a couple of traditional Bali Aga-style dwellings, and a large banyan tree, which is said to be more than 1,100 years old. At Kuban sub-village close to Trunyan is a mysterious cemetery that is separated by the lake and accessible only by boat - there is no path along the steep walls of the crater rim.

The village of Trunyan itself is situated at the edge of Batur Lake. This location is inaccessible except by boat, and it takes around half an hour across the calm waters. Getting to Lake Batur takes around two hours drive to the northeast of Denpasar along the main road to Buleleng and through Bangli Regency.

Unlike the Balinese people, the people of Trunyan do not cremate or bury their dead, but just lay them out in bamboo cages to decompose, although strangely there is no stench. A macabre collection of skulls and bones lies on the stone platform and the surrounding areas.

The dead bodies don't produce bad smells because of the perfumed scents from a huge Taru Menyan tree growing nearby. Taru means 'tree' and Menyan means 'nice smell'. The name of Terunyan was also derived from these two words.

The women from Trunyan are prohibited from going to the cemetery when a dead body is carried there. This follows the deeply rooted belief that if a woman comes to the cemetery while a corpse is being carried there, there will be a disaster in the village, for example a landslide or a volcanic eruption. Such events have been frequent in the village's history, but whether women had anything to do with it is a matter of opinion...

You can visit both the village of Trunyan and the Kuban cemetery by chartered boat from Kedisan. Sadly, nowadays the boat trips are now blatant tourist traps, as touts and guides strongly urge you to donate your cash to the temple project or leave a donation for the dead. These touts ruin an otherwise fascinating experience.

Cascada Nungnung
description: Dicen que al que madruga Dios le ayuda si madruga con buen fin...Pues vaya que madrugamos para poder disfrutar de este bonito entorno de fácil acceso pero con la dificultad que supone sus mas de 500 escalones de bajada para poder toparnos con esta maravilla de catarata con el nombre de Nungnung también conocida como catarata Virgen. Y como al que madruga Dios le ayuda, pues tuvimos la suerte de disfrutar solo para nosotros  de este bonito entorno y así poder explayarme para realizar distintas fotografías como esta que espero que sea de vuestro agrado y como no después pegarme un chapuzón debajo de la fría agua de la cascada. Y como bien he dicho antes sobre  la pequeña dificultad de los más de 500 escalones para su acceso ahora toca subirlos para abandonar el lugar, pero he de decir que mereció la pena este pequeño inconveniente.

title: Visite Ubud
description:
Forêt des singes et palais royal.

La forêt des singes d'Ubud est une réserve naturelle sacrée, située à l'extrémité sud de Jalan Monkey Forest. Elle abrite le temple de Dalem Agung Padantegal et plus de 600 macaques à longue queue (Macaca fascicularis) (en 2016).

À proximité du marché traditionnel, et à l'intersection de la Jalan Monkey Forest et Jalan Raya Ubud, se trouve le vaste palais Puri Saren Agung. La maison de Tjokorda Agung Gede Sukawati (1910-1978), dernier "roi" d'Ubud, est maintenant occupée par ses descendants et des spectacles de danse ont lieu dans sa cour. C'est aussi l'un des premiers hôtels d'Ubud, datant de 1930.

title: Plage de Nusa Dua Bali
description:
Nusa Dua est une localité située sur la péninsule de Bukit, dans le sud de l'île de Bali. Elle se trouve à environ 40 kilomètres au sud de Denpasar, la capitale de la province de Bali.

L'endroit abrite de nombreux lieux touristiques liés à son littoral de calcaire corallien, tels Jimbaran Beach et Garuda Wisnu Kencana. Les premiers investissements sur le site ont débuté en 1973 avec l'aide la Banque mondiale.

La plage de Nusa Dua est notamment appréciée pour la pratique du kitesurf.

Elle est le lieu où se tient en décembre 2007 la conférence de Bali consacrée aux problèmes des changements climatiques mondiaux.

Mother and Little Cutie at Pura Besakih, Bali
description:
Batur Bagus Cottages
The last day of the Kedisan celebrations for the mass cremation of 55 people. It is 4 years since the last Kedisan cremation and virtually all the villagers returned to Kedisan for the 10 days of Balinese Hindu rituals. Over 1000 people joined the final day of ceremonies, a pilgrimage to East Bali for scattering of ashes at the beach , a picnic lunch and a special ceremony at Pura Goa Lawah for babies who died through miscarriage. From there the final leg of the journey was to the mother temple of Bali, Pura Besakih.

title: Trunyan village cemetery, Lake Batur, Bali
description:
The village of Trunyan is squeezed tightly between the lake and the outer crater rim of Batur, an almighty volcano in Kintamani. This is a Bali Aga village, inhabited by descendants of the original Balinese, the people who predate the arrival of the Hindu Majapahit kingdom in the 16th century. It is famous for the Pura Pancering Jagat temple, but unfortunately visitors are not allowed inside. There are also a couple of traditional Bali Aga-style dwellings, and a large banyan tree, which is said to be more than 1,100 years old. At Kuban sub-village close to Trunyan is a mysterious cemetery that is separated by the lake and accessible only by boat - there is no path along the steep walls of the crater rim.

The village of Trunyan itself is situated at the edge of Batur Lake. This location is inaccessible except by boat, and it takes around half an hour across the calm waters. Getting to Lake Batur takes around two hours drive to the northeast of Denpasar along the main road to Buleleng and through Bangli Regency.

Unlike the Balinese people, the people of Trunyan do not cremate or bury their dead, but just lay them out in bamboo cages to decompose, although strangely there is no stench. A macabre collection of skulls and bones lies on the stone platform and the surrounding areas.

The dead bodies don't produce bad smells because of the perfumed scents from a huge Taru Menyan tree growing nearby. Taru means 'tree' and Menyan means 'nice smell'. The name of Terunyan was also derived from these two words.

The women from Trunyan are prohibited from going to the cemetery when a dead body is carried there. This follows the deeply rooted belief that if a woman comes to the cemetery while a corpse is being carried there, there will be a disaster in the village, for example a landslide or a volcanic eruption. Such events have been frequent in the village's history, but whether women had anything to do with it is a matter of opinion...

You can visit both the village of Trunyan and the Kuban cemetery by chartered boat from Kedisan. Sadly, nowadays the boat trips are now blatant tourist traps, as touts and guides strongly urge you to donate your cash to the temple project or leave a donation for the dead. These touts ruin an otherwise fascinating experience.

title: Balinese women in traditional kebaya & sarong
Gamelan Angklung. Pura Pulé, Mas, on Odalan day (Kuningan)
description: The gamelan angklung is one of the most popular types of orchestra in Bali, requiring about twenty musicians. Tuned to a four-tone scale in slendro tuning, the gamelan angklung presents a cheerful, open, and rhythmically intricate musical landscape, expressed in the fluid grace of its traditional repertoire. Although gamelan angklung is often heard in the Balinese temple, where it can supply musical accompaniment to a normal odalan (temple anniversary), its most characteristic and identifying context is in rituals related to death, and therefore to the invisible spiritual world of transitions from life to death and beyond. ( gsj.org/angklung )

description: Le monastère Brahma Vihara Arama, est le seul monastère bouddhique à Bali situé en pleine nature  sur une colline au Sud Ouest de Lovina.  Cet ensemble architectural est très différent des temples balinais et le jardin, orné de statures impressionnantes vaut le déplacement. On y aperçoit des moines en prières . title: Trunyan village cemetery, Lake Batur, Bali
description:
The village of Trunyan is squeezed tightly between the lake and the outer crater rim of Batur, an almighty volcano in Kintamani. This is a Bali Aga village, inhabited by descendants of the original Balinese, the people who predate the arrival of the Hindu Majapahit kingdom in the 16th century. It is famous for the Pura Pancering Jagat temple, but unfortunately visitors are not allowed inside. There are also a couple of traditional Bali Aga-style dwellings, and a large banyan tree, which is said to be more than 1,100 years old. At Kuban sub-village close to Trunyan is a mysterious cemetery that is separated by the lake and accessible only by boat - there is no path along the steep walls of the crater rim.

The village of Trunyan itself is situated at the edge of Batur Lake. This location is inaccessible except by boat, and it takes around half an hour across the calm waters. Getting to Lake Batur takes around two hours drive to the northeast of Denpasar along the main road to Buleleng and through Bangli Regency.

Unlike the Balinese people, the people of Trunyan do not cremate or bury their dead, but just lay them out in bamboo cages to decompose, although strangely there is no stench. A macabre collection of skulls and bones lies on the stone platform and the surrounding areas.

The dead bodies don't produce bad smells because of the perfumed scents from a huge Taru Menyan tree growing nearby. Taru means 'tree' and Menyan means 'nice smell'. The name of Terunyan was also derived from these two words.

The women from Trunyan are prohibited from going to the cemetery when a dead body is carried there. This follows the deeply rooted belief that if a woman comes to the cemetery while a corpse is being carried there, there will be a disaster in the village, for example a landslide or a volcanic eruption. Such events have been frequent in the village's history, but whether women had anything to do with it is a matter of opinion...

You can visit both the village of Trunyan and the Kuban cemetery by chartered boat from Kedisan. Sadly, nowadays the boat trips are now blatant tourist traps, as touts and guides strongly urge you to donate your cash to the temple project or leave a donation for the dead. These touts ruin an otherwise fascinating experience.

title: Plage de Nusa Dua Bali
description:

La plage de Nusa Dua est notamment appréciée pour la pratique du kitesurf.

Nusa Dua est une localité située sur la péninsule de Bukit, dans le sud de l'île de Bali. Elle se trouve à environ 40 kilomètres au sud de Denpasar, la capitale de la province de Bali.

L'endroit abrite de nombreux lieux touristiques liés à son littoral de calcaire corallien, tels Jimbaran Beach et Garuda Wisnu Kencana. Les premiers investissements sur le site ont débuté en 1973 avec l'aide la Banque mondiale.

La plage de Nusa Dua est notamment appréciée pour la pratique du kitesurf.

Elle est le lieu où se tient en décembre 2007 la conférence de Bali consacrée aux problèmes des changements climatiques mondiaux.

Trunyan village cemetery, Lake Batur, Bali
description:
The village of Trunyan is squeezed tightly between the lake and the outer crater rim of Batur, an almighty volcano in Kintamani. This is a Bali Aga village, inhabited by descendants of the original Balinese, the people who predate the arrival of the Hindu Majapahit kingdom in the 16th century. It is famous for the Pura Pancering Jagat temple, but unfortunately visitors are not allowed inside. There are also a couple of traditional Bali Aga-style dwellings, and a large banyan tree, which is said to be more than 1,100 years old. At Kuban sub-village close to Trunyan is a mysterious cemetery that is separated by the lake and accessible only by boat - there is no path along the steep walls of the crater rim.

The village of Trunyan itself is situated at the edge of Batur Lake. This location is inaccessible except by boat, and it takes around half an hour across the calm waters. Getting to Lake Batur takes around two hours drive to the northeast of Denpasar along the main road to Buleleng and through Bangli Regency.

Unlike the Balinese people, the people of Trunyan do not cremate or bury their dead, but just lay them out in bamboo cages to decompose, although strangely there is no stench. A macabre collection of skulls and bones lies on the stone platform and the surrounding areas.

The dead bodies don't produce bad smells because of the perfumed scents from a huge Taru Menyan tree growing nearby. Taru means 'tree' and Menyan means 'nice smell'. The name of Terunyan was also derived from these two words.

The women from Trunyan are prohibited from going to the cemetery when a dead body is carried there. This follows the deeply rooted belief that if a woman comes to the cemetery while a corpse is being carried there, there will be a disaster in the village, for example a landslide or a volcanic eruption. Such events have been frequent in the village's history, but whether women had anything to do with it is a matter of opinion...

You can visit both the village of Trunyan and the Kuban cemetery by chartered boat from Kedisan. Sadly, nowadays the boat trips are now blatant tourist traps, as touts and guides strongly urge you to donate your cash to the temple project or leave a donation for the dead. These touts ruin an otherwise fascinating experience.

title: Visite Ubud
description:
Forêt des singes et palais royal.

La forêt des singes d'Ubud est une réserve naturelle sacrée, située à l'extrémité sud de Jalan Monkey Forest. Elle abrite le temple de Dalem Agung Padantegal et plus de 600 macaques à longue queue (Macaca fascicularis) (en 2016).

À proximité du marché traditionnel, et à l'intersection de la Jalan Monkey Forest et Jalan Raya Ubud, se trouve le vaste palais Puri Saren Agung. La maison de Tjokorda Agung Gede Sukawati (1910-1978), dernier "roi" d'Ubud, est maintenant occupée par ses descendants et des spectacles de danse ont lieu dans sa cour. C'est aussi l'un des premiers hôtels d'Ubud, datant de 1930.

Getting to Lake Batur takes around two hours drive to the northeast of Denpasar along the main road to Buleleng and through Bangli Regency.

Unlike the Balinese people, the people of Trunyan do not cremate or bury their dead, but just lay them out in bamboo cages to decompose, although strangely there is no stench. A macabre collection of skulls and bones lies on the stone platform and the surrounding areas.

The dead bodies don't produce bad smells because of the perfumed scents from a huge Taru Menyan tree growing nearby. Taru means 'tree' and Menyan means 'nice smell'. The name of Terunyan was also derived from these two words.

The women from Trunyan are prohibited from going to the cemetery when a dead body is carried there. This follows the deeply rooted belief that if a woman comes to the cemetery while a corpse is being carried there, there will be a disaster in the village, for example a landslide or a volcanic eruption. Such events have been frequent in the village's history, but whether women had anything to do with it is a matter of opinion...

You can visit both the village of Trunyan and the Kuban cemetery by chartered boat from Kedisan. Sadly, nowadays the boat trips are now blatant tourist traps, as touts and guides strongly urge you to donate your cash to the temple project or leave a donation for the dead. These touts ruin an otherwise fascinating experience.

title: Visite Ubud
description:
Forêt des singes et palais royal.

La forêt des singes d'Ubud est une réserve naturelle sacrée, située à l'extrémité sud de Jalan Monkey Forest. Elle abrite le temple de Dalem Agung Padantegal et plus de 600 macaques à longue queue (Macaca fascicularis) (en 2016).

À proximité du marché traditionnel, et à l'intersection de la Jalan Monkey Forest et Jalan Raya Ubud, se trouve le vaste palais Puri Saren Agung. La maison de Tjokorda Agung Gede Sukawati (1910-1978), dernier "roi" d'Ubud, est maintenant occupée par ses descendants et des spectacles de danse ont lieu dans sa cour. C'est aussi l'un des premiers hôtels d'Ubud, datant de 1930.

title: Plage de Nusa Dua Bali
description:
Nusa Dua est une localité située sur la péninsule de Bukit, dans le sud de l'île de Bali. Elle se trouve à environ 40 kilomètres au sud de Denpasar, la capitale de la province de Bali.

L'endroit abrite de nombreux lieux touristiques liés à son littoral de calcaire corallien, tels Jimbaran Beach et Garuda Wisnu Kencana. Les premiers investissements sur le site ont débuté en 1973 avec l'aide la Banque mondiale.

La plage de Nusa Dua est notamment appréciée pour la pratique du kitesurf.

Elle est le lieu où se tient en décembre 2007 la conférence de Bali consacrée aux problèmes des changements climatiques mondiaux.

description:
Batur Bagus Cottages
The last day of the Kedisan celebrations for the mass cremation of 55 people. It is 4 years since the last Kedisan cremation and virtually all the villagers returned to Kedisan for the 10 days of Balinese Hindu rituals. Over 1000 people joined the final day of ceremonies, a pilgrimage to East Bali for scattering of ashes at the beach , a picnic lunch and a special ceremony at Pura Goa Lawah for babies who died through miscarriage. From there the final leg of the journey was to the mother temple of Bali, Pura Besakih.

title: Masks, Candi Kuning Tourist and Fruit Market
description: The people of Bali, Indonesia, perform numerous traditional dances. The dance most popular with tourists is the Barong & Rangda, a battle between good and evil. Barong is a strange creature, part shaggy dog, part lion, propelled like a circus horse by two dancers and the symbol of all things good. Barong wears a wooden mask like a large animal head ,beautifully carved and brightly coloured in red, white, black and gold. It is topped by a crown extending outwards to the sides of the head. The widow-witch Rangda is the queen of death and devourer of children. She practices the destructive forces of black magic and all things evil. Her mask is dark and fore boding, with a protruding red and gold tongue of fire. Of course Barong always triumphs over evil Rangda and saves all the unfortunate beings from stabbing themselves to death!

title: Panorama of the front façade of a Balinese temple
description:
Paduraksa, also known as kori is a type of gateway covered with towering roof that can be found in the island of Java and Bali, Indonesia. This architectural feature is commonly found in buildings from the classical Hindu-Buddhist period of Indonesia. Paduraksa marks the threshold into the most sacred space (the inner sanctum) within a religious compound, a cemetery, or a palace. In Balinese architecture, an elaborately decorated towering paduraksa is often built as the temple's most imposing structure.

While the basic form of a paduraksa is of a stepped candi, it can be heavily decorated with ornaments, figures, and symbols. In Bali, the crown of the paduraksa is decorated with flame-like ornaments and celestial figures. The menacing head of the bhoma or fierce kala is often carved over the opening, while a lion-like effigies, or a pair of fierce giants of dvarapalas, guard the sides of the entrance. Both menacing figures of kala's head and dvarapalas door guardians, are believed to have protective property; to repel and drive away evil spirits from entering the compound.

The main kori that marks the threshold into the inner sanctum of the main shrine is known as the kori agung ("great kori"). A paduraksa in the Islamic cemetery complex of Sendang Duwur contains a mysterious wing-like feature thought to represent the wings of the meru; this might be associated with the celestial bird garuda [Wikipedia.org]

title: Kuta Beach Bali
description:
Kuta is administratively a district (kecamatan) and subdistrict/village (kelurahan) in southern Bali, Indonesia.[3] A former fishing village, it was one of the first towns on Bali to see substantial tourist development, and as a beach resort remains one of Indonesia's major tourist destinations. It is known internationally for its long sandy beach, varied accommodation, many restaurants and bars, and many renowned surfers who visit from Australia. It is located near Bali's Ngurah Rai Airport.

The beach has been notable since early 1970s. Kuta beach is also known as Sunset Beach, as opposed to the Sunrise Beach, another name for Sanur Beach. Luxury resorts, restaurants, and clubs are located along the beach.

The adiparwa of the Indian Mahabharata epic tells a story of the demon Kalarau who drinks the elixir of life. The sun and the moon warn the deities, who decapitate kalarau as the liquid enters his mouth. In revenge the immortal head of Kalarau swallows the sun and the moon goddess Ratih, causing eclipses. At the end of an eclipse she emerges intact from his severed neck.

description:
From far away people were listening to the sonority of a big orchester playing the traditionel Balinesian Gamelan music.
The word Gamelan comes from the ancient roots "gambel" (Bali) and "gamel" (Java). Gambel means to play, musically. In Indonesian languages define gambel as to make a sound by striking or playing a musical instrument, such as a gong or a drum (in Indonesian Pukul Bunyi Bunyi. Bunyi means to sound. It also means to ring or to blow.

title: Trunyan village cemetery, Lake Batur, Bali
description:
The village of Trunyan is squeezed tightly between the lake and the outer crater rim of Batur, an almighty volcano in Kintamani. This is a Bali Aga village, inhabited by descendants of the original Balinese, the people who predate the arrival of the Hindu Majapahit kingdom in the 16th century. It is famous for the Pura Pancering Jagat temple, but unfortunately visitors are not allowed inside. There are also a couple of traditional Bali Aga-style dwellings, and a large banyan tree, which is said to be more than 1,100 years old. At Kuban sub-village close to Trunyan is a mysterious cemetery that is separated by the lake and accessible only by boat - there is no path along the steep walls of the crater rim.

The village of Trunyan itself is situated at the edge of Batur Lake. This location is inaccessible except by boat, and it takes around half an hour across the calm waters. Getting to Lake Batur takes around two hours drive to the northeast of Denpasar along the main road to Buleleng and through Bangli Regency.

Unlike the Balinese people, the people of Trunyan do not cremate or bury their dead, but just lay them out in bamboo cages to decompose, although strangely there is no stench. A macabre collection of skulls and bones lies on the stone platform and the surrounding areas.

The dead bodies don't produce bad smells because of the perfumed scents from a huge Taru Menyan tree growing nearby. Taru means 'tree' and Menyan means 'nice smell'. The name of Terunyan was also derived from these two words.

The women from Trunyan are prohibited from going to the cemetery when a dead body is carried there. This follows the deeply rooted belief that if a woman comes to the cemetery while a corpse is being carried there, there will be a disaster in the village, for example a landslide or a volcanic eruption. Such events have been frequent in the village's history, but whether women had anything to do with it is a matter of opinion...

You can visit both the village of Trunyan and the Kuban cemetery by chartered boat from Kedisan. Sadly, nowadays the boat trips are now blatant tourist traps, as touts and guides strongly urge you to donate your cash to the temple project or leave a donation for the dead. These touts ruin an otherwise fascinating experience.

title: Lord Ganesha
description:
Ganesh est un dieu d'une tres grande importance à Bali.
C'est un dieu protecteur du foyer puissant et paisible bien que possédant une expression tres douce tres humaine.
C'est également est un dieu rural, protecteur des moissons et sa monture est le rat,qu'il maitrise de ses puissantes pattes afin de protéger les récoltes.
Ganesh is a god of a very big importance in Bali.
It is the protective god of the powerful and peaceful home(foyer) although that possessing a very human very soft expression.
It is also is a rural, protective god of the harvests and his frame is the rat, which he masters of his pates powerful to protect the harvests.

description:
A beautiful tapestry of street art, the best I have seen in a long time. This mural was painted on a wall, at the roadside just outside Ubud, Bali. An enchanting mix of horror and comedy. The Babelfish informs me 'Pariwisata' is Indonesian for 'Tourist', although it appears remarkably similar to Parasite in English...

I love the thin black outline and bright white fill.  Not captured in the photo are the tourists whizzing past in oblivion on their mopeds. Satire at its finest.

title: Galungan on beach side
description: One of Bali’s major festivals celebrates the return of Balinese gods and ancestors to Bali. For ten days, Balinese families will entertain and welcome with prayers and offerings, along with ceremonies to cleanse and balance the inner and outer energy of the island. Galungan features, among other things, barong dancing from temple to temple in the village. The festival symbolizes the victory of good over evil. The origin of Galungan is a mystery, but essentially it is believed to be the beginning of the week in which the gods and ancestors descend to earth, and good triumphs over evil.

title: DSC04273
description: "Babayaga Tattoo" The greatest thing I can say about Canggu is that the gentrification process seems to have weeded out all classic tourist traps (shops hawking t-shirts with funny prints, etc) in favour of high-end eateries and small boutique shops. So the food is great but my feeling was a little bit like I could've been anywhere in the world, which to me is a bit sad. This particular evening I couldn't order any food since no one at the restaurant understood my questions regarding peanuts (hello allergy!) so instead I passed the time taking a few pictures from the restaurant balcony overlooking the street below.

title: As Radiant as the Sun...
description:
The beautiful Sun Conure (Aratinga solstitialis) with its colourful feathers seen at the Bali Bird Park, Bali, Indonesia (Captive). They are one of avicultures most stunning small parrots.

Both the adult male and female have similar appearance; they primarily have a golden-yellow plumage with orange-flushed underparts and face. They can grow up to 30 cm (12 in) long and typically weighs about 110g (4 oz). 

These birds normally feed on seeds, nuts, fruits, flowers, and insects. Unfortunately, in the wild, they are currently threatened by loss of habitat and trapping for their plumage or the pet trade and have been  listed as endangered by the IUCN.

The Crowning Glory
description:
This sexy guy right here is a Grey Crowned Crane (Balearica regulorum). 

These species of crane got its name from its predominantly grey body plumage and the crown of stiff golden feathers on its head! 

It can grow up to 1m (3.3 ft) tall, weighs 3.5 kg (7.7 lbs) and has a wingspan of 2 m (6.5 ft). 

These cranes are omnivores. Their diet may consist of plants, grain, seeds, worms, insects, frogs, small fishes and the eggs of aquatic animals.

Taken at Bali Bird Park, Bali, Indonesia, 2015.

title: Kuta Beach Bali
description:
Kuta is administratively a district (kecamatan) and subdistrict/village (kelurahan) in southern Bali, Indonesia.[3] A former fishing village, it was one of the first towns on Bali to see substantial tourist development, and as a beach resort remains one of Indonesia's major tourist destinations. It is known internationally for its long sandy beach, varied accommodation, many restaurants and bars, and many renowned surfers who visit from Australia. It is located near Bali's Ngurah Rai Airport.

The beach has been notable since early 1970s. Kuta beach is also known as Sunset Beach, as opposed to the Sunrise Beach, another name for Sanur Beach. Luxury resorts, restaurants, and clubs are located along the beach.

description: The Kecak Fire Dance is a traditional dance in Bali, Indonesia.The plot is based on a fragment from the Ramayana, the Hindu epic, and is unique in that the accompanying music is provided by the human voice, the gamelan suara, a choir of a dozens of men sitting in concentric circles, swaying, standing up, lying prone as the story develops. During the finale of the Fire Dance, a dancer throws himself into the flames of a fire. He can barely be seen through the smoke, sparks and flying palm husks. 11/09/2017 www.allenfotowild.com

Kuta Beach Bali
description:
Kuta is administratively a district (kecamatan) and subdistrict/village (kelurahan) in southern Bali, Indonesia.[3] A former fishing village, it was one of the first towns on Bali to see substantial tourist development, and as a beach resort remains one of Indonesia's major tourist destinations. It is known internationally for its long sandy beach, varied accommodation, many restaurants and bars, and many renowned surfers who visit from Australia. It is located near Bali's Ngurah Rai Airport.

The beach has been notable since early 1970s. Kuta beach is also known as Sunset Beach, as opposed to the Sunrise Beach, another name for Sanur Beach. Luxury resorts, restaurants, and clubs are located along the beach.

title: The Villa Kitty Kitty.
description:
I really got to appreciate the work that Elizabeth and her staff do at "Villa Kitty" near Ubud, Bali. Many people are supportive of such animal welfare programs in Bali like BAWA however Villa Kitty can go largely unnoticed.

I would personally recommend looking them up online, visiting the next time you're in Bali and seeing the wonderful work they're doing, donating and helping in whatever way possible.

title: Pura Besakih, Bali
description:
Batur Bagus Cottages
The last day of the Kedisan celebrations for the mass cremation of 55 people. It is 4 years since the last Kedisan cremation and virtually all the villagers returned to Kedisan for the 10 days of Balinese Hindu rituals. Over 1000 people joined the final day of ceremonies, a pilgrimage to East Bali for scattering of ashes at the beach , a picnic lunch and a special ceremony at Pura Goa Lawah for babies who died through miscarriage. From there the final leg of the journey was to the mother temple of Bali, Pura Besakih.

title: Nungnung waterfall
description:
A novecientos metros sobre el nivel del mar, en una pequeña aldea en medio de la nada, la cascada Nungnung nos estaba esperando. 

Escuchar y mirar miles de litros de agua que caen en cascada a más 50 metros de altura a una hermosa piscina, no tiene precio.

Suena precioso? Sin embargo, llegar allí es un verdadero desafío. Situado en la parte inferior de un desfiladero, hay que descender hasta 509 escalones para llegar a las cataratas. Pero ser recibido con una magnífica vista de las cascadas, sin duda es una imagen perfecta y merece la pena. 

Después de las fotos de rigor, toca un bañito, en esas agua cristalinas para reponer fuerzas, ya que ahora viene lo peor...subir los 509 escalones!! Pero bueno como podéis ver en la foto, la experiencia mereció la pena.

title: Trunyan village cemetery, Lake Batur, Bali
description:
The village of Trunyan is squeezed tightly between the lake and the outer crater rim of Batur, an almighty volcano in Kintamani. This is a Bali Aga village, inhabited by descendants of the original Balinese, the people who predate the arrival of the Hindu Majapahit kingdom in the 16th century. It is famous for the Pura Pancering Jagat temple, but unfortunately visitors are not allowed inside. There are also a couple of traditional Bali Aga-style dwellings, and a large banyan tree, which is said to be more than 1,100 years old. At Kuban sub-village close to Trunyan is a mysterious cemetery that is separated by the lake and accessible only by boat - there is no path along the steep walls of the crater rim.

The village of Trunyan itself is situated at the edge of Batur Lake. This location is inaccessible except by boat, and it takes around half an hour across the calm waters. Getting to Lake Batur takes around two hours drive to the northeast of Denpasar along the main road to Buleleng and through Bangli Regency.

Unlike the Balinese people, the people of Trunyan do not cremate or bury their dead, but just lay them out in bamboo cages to decompose, although strangely there is no stench. A macabre collection of skulls and bones lies on the stone platform and the surrounding areas.

The dead bodies don't produce bad smells because of the perfumed scents from a huge Taru Menyan tree growing nearby. Taru means 'tree' and Menyan means 'nice smell'. The name of Terunyan was also derived from these two words.

The women from Trunyan are prohibited from going to the cemetery when a dead body is carried there. This follows the deeply rooted belief that if a woman comes to the cemetery while a corpse is being carried there, there will be a disaster in the village, for example a landslide or a volcanic eruption. Such events have been frequent in the village's history, but whether women had anything to do with it is a matter of opinion...

You can visit both the village of Trunyan and the Kuban cemetery by chartered boat from Kedisan. Sadly, nowadays the boat trips are now blatant tourist traps, as touts and guides strongly urge you to donate your cash to the temple project or leave a donation for the dead. These touts ruin an otherwise fascinating experience.

description:
Kuta is administratively a district (kecamatan) and subdistrict/village (kelurahan) in southern Bali, Indonesia.[3] A former fishing village, it was one of the first towns on Bali to see substantial tourist development, and as a beach resort remains one of Indonesia's major tourist destinations. It is located near Bali's Ngurah Rai Airport.

The beach has been notable since early 1970s. Kuta beach is also known as Sunset Beach, as opposed to the Sunrise Beach, another name for Sanur Beach. Luxury resorts, restaurants, and clubs are located along the beach.

title: Kuta Beach Bali
description:
Kuta is administratively a district (kecamatan) and subdistrict/village (kelurahan) in southern Bali, Indonesia.[3] A former fishing village, it was one of the first towns on Bali to see substantial tourist development, and as a beach resort remains one of Indonesia's major tourist destinations. It is known internationally for its long sandy beach, varied accommodation, many restaurants and bars, and many renowned surfers who visit from Australia. It is located near Bali's Ngurah Rai Airport.

The beach has been notable since early 1970s. Kuta beach is also known as Sunset Beach, as opposed to the Sunrise Beach, another name for Sanur Beach. Luxury resorts, restaurants, and clubs are located along the beach.

title: Kayusalem Temple, Pura Besakih, Bali
description:
Batur Bagus Cottages
The last day of the Kedisan celebrations for the mass cremation of 55 people. It is 4 years since the last Kedisan cremation and virtually all the villagers returned to Kedisan for the 10 days of Balinese Hindu rituals. Over 1000 people joined the final day of ceremonies, a pilgrimage to East Bali for scattering of ashes at the beach , a picnic lunch and a special ceremony at Pura Goa Lawah for babies who died through miscarriage. From there the final leg of the journey was to the mother temple of Bali, Pura Besakih.

title: The luwak in the cage
description:
Meanwhile its a common business on Bali to produce the Kopi Luwak and for this reasons people are holding the Luwak animal encosed in cages.
Most people keep the meaning the expensive coffee is the product of cats but this is absolute an hooey. Cats never eat coffee cherries, cats eat fish and meat.
The Luwak is an animal like a weasel or the Asian palm civet - never a cat!
Here I post my photo captured in Bali Pulina a famouse Coffee plantage nearby Ubud.
(Its very difficult to get the Luwak in front of the camera in the wild, the animal moving very fast and seen only at night. But its reprehensible too to keep the animals in cages just for making business with the most expensive coffee.)

title: Restaurant dans une rizière
description:
Village de Tegalalang, Ubud, Bali, Indonésie.
Le "Green Kubu" un adorable restaurant situé au sommet de rizières en terrasses.
Les propriétaires ont eut l'idée de remplacer le riz des terrasses les plus proches par des nénuphars. Une splendeur! 
On ne peut y accéder qu'à pied. 
Et surtout on y mange fort bien de délicieuses spécialités indonésiennes, à des prix très raisonnables, compter 5 € par personne!

title: Kuta Beach Bali
description:
Kuta is administratively a district (kecamatan) and subdistrict/village (kelurahan) in southern Bali, Indonesia.[3] A former fishing village, it was one of the first towns on Bali to see substantial tourist development, and as a beach resort remains one of Indonesia's major tourist destinations. It is known internationally for its long sandy beach, varied accommodation, many restaurants and bars, and many renowned surfers who visit from Australia. It is located near Bali's Ngurah Rai Airport.

The beach has been notable since early 1970s. Kuta beach is also known as Sunset Beach, as opposed to the Sunrise Beach, another name for Sanur Beach. Luxury resorts, restaurants, and clubs are located along the beach.

title: 11-Tiered meru dedicated to Dewi Danu 6751
description: My visit to the temple of Pura Ulun Danu Beratan in central Bali was with full raincoat and my trusty iPhone. Even in the wet, it is a beautiful place. Shrines of varying sizes and shapes are dotted around the grounds. The mountain in the background disappear into the rainclouds. Pura Beratan is a major Shaivite water temple complex, part of the UNESCO-listed Subak water management system. The 11-storey Pelinggih Meru is dedicated to Shiva and his consort Parvathi, and also enshrines a Buddha statue. For the story, please visit: www.ursulasweeklywanders.com/travel/balis-pura-ulun-danu-...

title: Portrait of Bonnie.
description:
Our beautiful Bali dog, rescued after she had been abandoned by her owner in Ubud at the back of a warung. Bonnie was apparently a "nuisance" at the Villa where she was from, the customers complained. She was dumped for others to take care of which did not really occur, how many dogs survive on a bit of rice?

 Eventually the western owner did not return and my partner was taking care of her, feeding her. Soon, there were complaints at her accommodation where Bonnie had been dumped. The owner decided that Bonnie would be taken away and either dumped or killed. We stepped in and saved her.

Bonnie (not her original name) lives with us and although she has her anxiety issues she is much happier, healthier and relaxed than she was living the life of a stray. Bonnie is very sophisticated too, loving classical music and opera. She's also a fussy eater and prefers fresh ayam goreng (fried chicken) over anything else.

We love our dog and she never needs to fear ever being dumped again.

title: Roasting most expensive coffee on the world
description:
Kopi luwak or civet coffee is a coffee made from the beans of coffee berries which have been eaten by the Asian Palm Civet and other related civets, then passed through its digestive tract.
A civet eats the berries for their fleshy pulp. In its stomach, proteolytic enzymes seep into the beans, making shorter peptides and more free amino acids. Passing through a civet's intestines the beans are then defecated, keeping their shape. After gathering, thorough washing, sun drying, light roasting and brewing, these beans yield an aromatic coffee with much less bitterness, widely noted as the most expensive coffee in the world.
The boy is roasting fresh beans for preparing a cup of coffee for us.

title: Reflections of Bali
description: A jukung or canoe also known as cadik is a small wooden Indonesian outrigger canoe. It is a traditional fishing boat The colourful traditional fishing boats that line the coastal. These graceful vessels use only one main cloth sail and in favourable winds can skim them ocean’s surface at a fairly rapid pace. The Balinese generally use jukung for fishing. These boats will venture out into the coastal waters in the evening and return with their catch before sunrise to sell at local seafood markets. However, the impact of tourism has meant that many of the island’s traditional fishermen can now supplement their limited incomes by taking paying passengers to surf and snorkel at offshore reefs and neighbouring islands. Source www.tanahlot.net/home/index.php?option=com_content&vi.... en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jukung Bali_383.3

Batur Bagus Cottages
The last day of the Kedisan celebrations for the mass cremation of 50 people. It is 4 years since the last Kedisan cremation and virtually all the villagers returned to Kedisan for the 10 days of Balinese Hindu rituals. Over 1000 people joined the final day of ceremonies, a pilgrimage to East Bali for scattering of ashes at the beach , a picnic lunch and a special ceremony atq Pura Goa Lawah for babies who died through miscarriage. From there the final leg of the journey was to the mother temple of Bali, Pura Besakih.

title: Reflections of Bali
description: A jukung or canoe also known as cadik is a small wooden Indonesian outrigger canoe. It is a traditional fishing boat The colourful traditional fishing boats that line the coastal. These graceful vessels use only one main cloth sail and in favourable winds can skim them ocean’s surface at a fairly rapid pace. The Balinese generally use jukung for fishing. These boats will venture out into the coastal waters in the evening and return with their catch before sunrise to sell at local seafood markets. However, the impact of tourism has meant that many of the island’s traditional fishermen can now supplement their limited incomes by taking paying passengers to surf and snorkel at offshore reefs and neighbouring islands. title: Not Forgotten. Mads Lange Memorial, Kuta, Bali, Indonesia
description:
One of the reasons I made a stop-over of more than a day on Bali this time was to visit the relatively little know  memorial to a hero of mine, Mads Johansen Lange (1807-1856). Lange was an adventurous entrepreneur who shipped out of Denmark at age 14; after sailing to Tharangambadi - then the Danish colony Tranquebar - in the Indian Tamil Nadu, he cultivated a taste for the East. With his brothers he set out for Southeast Asia, and he was a merchant at Tanjungkarang near Ampenan and Mataram on Lombok in 1835. Lange became heavily involved in local politics between two Balinese rajahs there and also the Sasak population. Soon forced to flee to Bali (1839) by the skin of his teeth he made good there becoming outstandingly rich. Lange traded in spices, green tobacco, rice, cows and much more. A great share of this wealth he accrued by selling dried beef to the Dutch colonial troops on Java. He managed to hold his own in the highly changeable politics of Bali and the three Dutch armed expeditionary wars there. In fact, Lange was something of a peace broker, and in time was called 'the king of Bali'. Awarded a knighthood in the Netherlands Lion by King William III, he increasingly went his own way and became a thorn in the side of the Dutch. Rumor had it that Lange was gotten rid of by poisoning. 
Regardless, he was not forgotten. His warehouses were on the banks of the Tukad Mati (=Dead River, because it no longer has any function) of Kuta which merchant vessels could still navigate in Lange's times. Here he was buried. 
In 1927, the Dutch erected a small memorial on his grave; this was 'cleaned up' and enlarged by his descendants in 1996-1997; finally in 2007, a great restoration took place financed by family members from Denmark, Brazil, Singapore and Johor. Perhaps most notable in this is that the Sultans of Johor are proud of Lange as their ancestor. Lange's daughter Cecilia, taking the name of Zubaidah, had  married  Sultan Abu Bakar (1833-1895) in 1862; their son is the direct ancestor of the present Sultan. The latter's name figures prominently on the list of donors engraved on this memorial.
The inset photo is of Lange's bust next to the memorial. It was sculpted by Lars Calmar (1968-) of Rudkøbing, Denmark. The entire memorial is exceptionally well-kept and clean, and very well worth a visit even though it's a bit out of the way.

title: Visite Ubud
description:
Forêt des singes et palais royal.

La forêt des singes d'Ubud est une réserve naturelle sacrée, située à l'extrémité sud de Jalan Monkey Forest. Elle abrite le temple de Dalem Agung Padantegal et plus de 600 macaques à longue queue (Macaca fascicularis) (en 2016).

À proximité du marché traditionnel, et à l'intersection de la Jalan Monkey Forest et Jalan Raya Ubud, se trouve le vaste palais Puri Saren Agung. La maison de Tjokorda Agung Gede Sukawati (1910-1978), dernier "roi" d'Ubud, est maintenant occupée par ses descendants et des spectacles de danse ont lieu dans sa cour. C'est aussi l'un des premiers hôtels d'Ubud, datant de 1930.

title: Plage de Nusa Dua Bali
description:
Nusa Dua est une localité située sur la péninsule de Bukit, dans le sud de l'île de Bali. Elle se trouve à environ 40 kilomètres au sud de Denpasar, la capitale de la province de Bali.

L'endroit abrite de nombreux lieux touristiques liés à son littoral de calcaire corallien, tels Jimbaran Beach et Garuda Wisnu Kencana. Les premiers investissements sur le site ont débuté en 1973 avec l'aide la Banque mondiale.

La plage de Nusa Dua est notamment appréciée pour la pratique du kitesurf.

Elle est le lieu où se tient en décembre 2007 la conférence de Bali consacrée aux problèmes des changements climatiques mondiaux.

title: La danse du Barong dance.....Bali
description:
The barong is a dance stemming from the Balinese mythology. This term of Barong often indicates a huge lion considered as the Lord of the forest; this animistic worship is previous upon the arrival of the Hinduism on the island. On this photo of the men were bewitched by a devil who tries to make so that they commit suicide but the barong protects them from themselves.
.
Le barong est une danse issue de la mythologie Balinaise. Ce terme de Barong désigne souvent un lion géant considéré comme le seigneur de la forêt; ce culte animiste est antérieur à l'arrivée de l'hindouisme sur l'île. Sur cette photo des hommes ont étés envoûtés par un démon qui tente de faire en sorte qu'ils se suicident mais le barong les protège d'eux-mêmes.Remarquez le visage du danseur dans le Lion ,il semble souffrir de la chaleur....!!

title: Un retrato muy mono
description:
La información que pude obtener en mi visita a Monkey Forest, en la ciudad de Ubud sobre el Macaco de cola larga conocido también como Macaco Cangrejero, se puede decir que  es frecuente encontrarles en grandes grupos, en
prácticamente todo el sudeste asiático, ocupando tanto entornos urbanos como
naturales. Son unos de los primates con
mayor capacidad de adaptación.

Por lo visto esta especie se emplea en estudios médicos. Después que se puso restricciones en la exportación del Macaco Rhesus , el Macaco Cangrejero lo ha sustituido en muchos estudios. En la isla Tinjil, en Indonesia, se ha creado una colonia con el propósito de criarlos para estos fines.

El Macaco Cangrejero es principalmente de hábitos arborícolas. Durante el día es muy probable que se mantenga dentro de la vegetación. Por la mañana y por la tarde, al menos algunas poblaciones, visitan la orilla del río u otro depósito de agua...(de hay lo de Macaco cangrejero)

Este mono es un excelente nadador. Se sumerge bajo la superficie y nada en busca de alimentos que se encuentran en el fondo, los cuales, tan pronto los obtiene, regresa a la orilla.

La longitud que llegan a alcanzar estos animales esta entre 38 y 64 cm, la longitud de su cola oscila entre los 40 y los 65 cm, suelen ser de mayor tamaño los machos. con el peso pasa lo mismo, de media, las hembras suelen pesar sobre los 4 kg, mientras el macho lo hace sobre los7 kg.

title: Taman Gili
description:
Taman Gili (Jardín de la isla) es la única parte del Palacio Real de Klungkung que se conserva en la actualidad.

Del esplendor del reino de Gelgel, que proporcionó a Klungkung poderío político y cultural en los ss. XVIII y XIX antes de que los holandeses destruyeran la ciudad, no queda casi nada. Pasada la puerta Sur (Pemedal Agung), magníficamente labrada, se admira el pabellón flotante (Bale Kambang), en medio de un estanque de nenúfares, y sus techos pintados por artistas locales.

title: Offerings at Pura Besakih, Bali
description:
Batur Bagus Cottages
The last day of the Kedisan celebrations for the mass cremation of 55 people. It is 4 years since the last Kedisan cremation and virtually all the villagers returned to Kedisan for the 10 days of Balinese Hindu rituals. Over 1000 people joined the final day of ceremonies, a pilgrimage to East Bali for scattering of ashes at the beach , a picnic lunch and a special ceremony at Pura Goa Lawah for babies who died through miscarriage. From there the final leg of the journey was to the mother temple of Bali, Pura Besakih.

title: Pura Ulun Danu Bratan
description:
Se suele decir que Bali es la isla de los 10.000 templos, y en un contexto de competencia tan feroz Ulan Danu puede presumir de ser uno de los más encantadores.

Construido en el siglo XVII sobre el lago Bratan, el segundo más grande de la isla, Ulan Danu está dedicado a Dewi Danu, diosa del agua, y es lugar de peregrinación sobre todo de campesinos, que acuden a él a pedir agua para sus cultivos.

Su importancia al proteger la principal fuente de irrigación de la zona es por tanto innegable, pero además, como podemos observar en la fotografía, su aspecto no puede ser más hermoso y elegante.

El lago Bratan, formado en el cráter del antiguo volcán Mount Catur, se encuentra a unos 1.200 metros de altitud, rodeado de verdes montañas y cubierto por una suave neblina. Todo ello, en conjunto, compone una estampa de ensueño. No por nada, esta imagen decora los billetes de 50.000 rupias.

Hanie Bee
description: My Bali Princess from my Bali session. It was not easy to get a model in Bali. The original model that I was in contact with while I was still in Montreal, was very slow in responding to my emails and I felt very uncertain that she will follow through. I absolutely wanted to do at least one session with one model during my Bali visit. Out of the 23 days in Bali, it would seem unlikely not to be able to book a model for even a single session. Well it turns out that the casting sites that I use for booking models are blocked in Indonesia due to their nudity content. Indonesia is a very religious country with strict morality laws on nudity. Luckily while still in Montreal, I cast a wider net than I really needed by contacting as many as 5 models. As it turned out one of them named Hanie was able to respond, and with the help of my friend Paul Saulnier, a Montreal expat photographer, we were able to set us the session. I hope that in the next little while you will be seeing a whole lot of Hanie. Tomorrow I will be doing the 24hr flight back to Montreal, so this will be my last posting for a bit. For my video patrons, the session with Hanie was filmed and I will eventually use some of the footage in my upcoming videos. Great photography requires dedication, time and effort. But above all there are costs involved as well. Equipment, props and model fees, not to mention time, are all "out-of-pocket" expenses for the artist. If you enjoy my photographic art, you might like to help to support it. To see behind-the-scenes videos and get a glimpse of my process, please follow the links below. My documentary Sol Lang on Naked Files Episode 11 More one-on-one Behind the scenes with photographer Sol Lang. Please note: Mature content Thanks for the support!

title: Temple d'Uluwatu
description:
L'accès au temple lui même est strictement réservé aux prêtres et fidèles à l'occasion d'importantes cérémonies. Il est d'une architecture plutôt classique et ne mérite pas grand intérêt. C'est surtout le paysage qui est grandiose.
L'immense domaine a été sécurisé, les sentiers et escaliers améliorés et des accès handicapés sont en cours de réalisation. Les singes ont été semi-domestiqués. Ils visent probablement un classement au patrimoine mondial de l'UNESCO.

Kuta Beach Bali
description:
Kuta is administratively a district (kecamatan) and subdistrict/village (kelurahan) in southern Bali, Indonesia.[3] A former fishing village, it was one of the first towns on Bali to see substantial tourist development, and as a beach resort remains one of Indonesia's major tourist destinations. It is known internationally for its long sandy beach, varied accommodation, many restaurants and bars, and many renowned surfers who visit from Australia. It is located near Bali's Ngurah Rai Airport.

The beach has been notable since early 1970s. Kuta beach is also known as Sunset Beach, as opposed to the Sunrise Beach, another name for Sanur Beach. Luxury resorts, restaurants, and clubs are located along the beach.

title: Canang sari
description:
A canang sari is an offering, made daily by the Balinese, in accordance with the Hindu religion. It is said to protect and bring luck. They are made by hand, everyday, and are often beautifully detailed. In the morning, incense is traditionally put into them; you can sometimes smell it in the streets. It is considered a bad omen to step on them, so you have to be careful when walking around town. 

Sometimes food is put into the canang saris – creatures, little and big, benefit from those offerings.

BALI_(636)
description: Le monastère Brahma Vihara Arama, est le seul monastère bouddhique à Bali situé en pleine nature  sur une colline au Sud Ouest de Lovina.  Cet ensemble architectural est très différent des temples balinais et le jardin, orné de statures impressionnantes vaut le déplacement. On y aperçoit des moines en prières . Il dispose de décorations colorées, un toit orange, des statues de Buddha, des sculptures balinaises et des gardiens aux portes. Cette belle structure se trouve dans un endroit  magnifique dotée de grands arbres de pin, des pelouses taillées, des jardins de fleurs bien entretenus et d'une vue plongeante sur la vallée, les champs de riz et la mer.

title: Temple sur l'eau Tirta Gangga
description: Construit par le raja de Karangasem au milieu du XXe siècle , le site de Tirta Gangga fut sinistré par l’éruption volcanique du mont Agung de 1963 et entièrement restauré pour retrouver ses grands bassins de nénuphars, traversés par des dalles au milieu de l’eau, sa piscine royale, ses statues majestueuses et ses espaces verts luxuriants.
